  <p><strong>Formal vs. informal email tone:</strong></p>

  <p>The level of formality in Chinese business emails depends heavily on your relationship with the recipient. For a first-time contact or someone senior to you, maximum formality is required — use 尊敬的 (zūnjìng de, respected) before their title, 您 (nín) throughout, and close with 此致敬礼 (cǐ zhì jìnglǐ). As the relationship develops over weeks or months, you can gradually shift to a warmer tone. With colleagues you know well, starting with 您好 (nín hǎo) or even the person's name directly is acceptable. Closing phrases can soften to 祝工作顺利 (zhù gōngzuò shùnlì) — wishing you smooth work — or 祝好 (zhù hǎo) — best wishes. However, when in doubt, always err on the side of being more formal. A slightly overly formal email is never offensive, while an overly casual one can damage your professional image. One important difference from Western email culture: Chinese professionals generally prefer shorter, more direct emails for routine matters and reserve longer, more elaborate emails for important proposals or formal requests.</p>

